{"ClientSettings":{"Pn":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"P"},"Sc":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"H"},"Qz":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"T"},"Ap":true,"Mute":true,"Lad":"2026-05-27T00:00:00Z","Iotd":0,"Gwb":0,"Tns":0,"Dft":null,"Mvs":0,"Flt":0,"Imp":1,"Tobn":0},"MediaContents":[{"ImageContent":{"Description":"As spring sweeps across Northern California in the United States, the landscape is transformed by the vibrant displays of lupine flowers in shades of blue, purple and white. Flourishing in the region's Mediterranean climate, these wildflowers provide a vital source of nectar for pollinators such as bees, butterflies and beetles. With over 200 species found worldwide, lupines range from coastal varieties to those that thrive in mountain meadows. Beyond their striking beauty, lupines are essential to the ecosystem: by fixing nitrogen underground, they enrich soil fertility and support the growth of surrounding plants, even in nutrient-poor environments.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.LupineBloom_ROW8766643120_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.LupineBloom_ROW8766643120_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Lupine flowers in bloom, Northern California, United States","Copyright":"© Jeffrey Lewis/Tandem Stills + Motion","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260526_LupineBloom\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Lupinus&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260526_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260526_LupineBloom"},"Ssd":"20260526","Name":"LupineBloom","Market":"ROW","Hash":"8766643120","FullDateString":"26. maj 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"What if a building could breathe? In the middle of Jaipur, Hawa Mahal does exactly that—pulling in air, pushing out heat and turning architecture into a quiet science experiment. It's less a palace, more a perfectly timed exhale. And yes, it really does live up to its name: the 'Palace of Winds.'","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.HawaMahal2026_ROW8601655471_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.HawaMahal2026_ROW8601655471_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"View over Jaipur from Hawa Mahal, Rajasthan","Copyright":"© byheaven/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260525_HawaMahal2026\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Hawa+Mahal&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260525_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260525_HawaMahal2026"},"Ssd":"20260525","Name":"HawaMahal2026","Market":"ROW","Hash":"8601655471","FullDateString":"25. maj 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Today's image highlights a prime example of long-term conservation efforts: Tre Cime Nature Park in northern Italy. Located in the Dolomites—a UNESCO World Heritage Site known for striking geology—the park was established in 1981. It is best known for the Tre Cime di Lavaredo: three towering dolomite peaks that rise sharply above alpine meadows. Their sheer rock faces make them among the Alps' most recognisable landmarks.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.DolomitesPark_ROW8331574098_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.DolomitesPark_ROW8331574098_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Tre Cime Nature Park, South Tyrol, Italy","Copyright":"© Adisorn Fineday Chutikunakorn/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260524_DolomitesPark\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Tre+Cime+Nature+Park&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260524_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260524_DolomitesPark"},"Ssd":"20260524","Name":"DolomitesPark","Market":"ROW","Hash":"8331574098","FullDateString":"24. maj 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Turtles are not only fascinating animals; they also play vital roles in nature. Sea turtles help keep seagrass beds and coral reefs healthy, while freshwater and land counterparts support balanced ecosystems. Their shells are part of their skeletons, formed from dozens of fused bones, and some species navigate using Earth's magnetic field to return to the beaches where they hatched.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.ThreeTurtlesButterflies_ROW8158760119_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.ThreeTurtlesButterflies_ROW8158760119_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Turtles with butterflies","Copyright":"© Patrick Gallet/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260523_ThreeTurtlesButterflies\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Turtles&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260523_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260523_ThreeTurtlesButterflies"},"Ssd":"20260523","Name":"ThreeTurtlesButterflies","Market":"ROW","Hash":"8158760119","FullDateString":"23. maj 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Naturally sculpted over 500,000 years, the Pont d'Arc in France opens like a gateway to the Ardèche Gorge. At dawn, its monumental silhouette glows with a golden hue as the murmur of the river echoes between limestone cliffs, where peregrine falcons and crag martins nest. You walk along the sandy bank, scented with wild mint and sun-warmed boxwood, with the feeling of stepping into a landscape that has remained unchanged since prehistoric times.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.PontArdeche_ROW1049828864_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.PontArdeche_ROW1049828864_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Pont d'Arc, Ardèche, France","Copyright":"© Gael Fontaine/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260522_PontArdeche\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Pont+dArc+Ardeche&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260522_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260522_PontArdeche"},"Ssd":"20260522","Name":"PontArdeche","Market":"ROW","Hash":"1049828864","FullDateString":"22. maj 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Today's image spotlights a drink that connects daily rituals to ancient landscapes. Just one look at the terraced tea fields of Sichuan Province, China, shows how deep those roots run. This misty region in southwest China is one of the earliest centres of tea culture, where people drank and cultivated tea more than 2,000 years ago. On nearby Mengding Mountain, a scholar named Wu Lizhen planted some of the world's first managed tea gardens during the Han Dynasty, laying the groundwork for generations of growers.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.SichuanTea_ROW1006834324_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.SichuanTea_ROW1006834324_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Tea terraces in Sichuan Province, China","Copyright":"© lzf/Shutterstock","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260521_SichuanTea\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Tea+terraces+in+Sichuan+Province&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260521_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260521_SichuanTea"},"Ssd":"20260521","Name":"SichuanTea","Market":"ROW","Hash":"1006834324","FullDateString":"21. maj 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"A soft buzz and a dusting of pollen can shape the future of our food. Today's image features the bumble bee during its quiet yet essential work. Unlike many insects, bumble bees use 'buzz pollination,' vibrating their flight muscles to shake pollen from flowers—a method vital for crops such as tomatoes, peppers and blueberries. Bees and other pollinators contribute to more than 75% of the world's major food crops, improving both yield and quality.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.BumbleBee_ROW7621208242_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.BumbleBee_ROW7621208242_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Bumble bee pollinating, Worcester, England","Copyright":"© SimonEastwood87/Shutterstock","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260520_BumbleBee\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Bumblebee&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260520_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260520_BumbleBee"},"Ssd":"20260520","Name":"BumbleBee","Market":"ROW","Hash":"7621208242","FullDateString":"20. maj 2026"}],"PreloadMediaContents":[{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Cutting a surreal path through the high-altitude deserts of western China, Xitai Jinaier Lake (also known as West Taijinar Lake) is a striking salt lake in the remote Qaidam Basin. A stretch of National Highway 315 runs directly across its shallow waters, creating the illusion of a road floating between two worlds. On one side, the water often appears deep blue; on the other, a softer green hue, a contrast shaped by differing mineral concentrations in the brine.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.Qinghai_ROW4654938866_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.Qinghai_ROW4654938866_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Highway through Xitai Jinaier Lake, Qinghai Province, China","Copyright":"© Kaicheng Xu/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260602_Qinghai\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Qaidam+Basin+China&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260602_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260602_Qinghai"},"Ssd":"20260602","Name":"Qinghai","Market":"ROW","Hash":"4654938866","FullDateString":"2. jun. 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Palermo, the capital of the island of Sicily in southern Italy, is a city where layers of history, art and culture meet in a vivid and sometimes chaotic harmony. Founded by the Phoenicians and later shaped by Romans, Arabs, Normans and Spaniards, it carries traces of many civilisations that passed through the Mediterranean. This rich past is visible in its architecture, from the Arab-Norman palaces and churches recognised by UNESCO to the Baroque facades that define its historic streets.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.OlivaPalermo_ROW4355319130_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.OlivaPalermo_ROW4355319130_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Palermo skyline at dusk, Sicily, Italy","Copyright":"© Sean Pavone/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260601_OlivaPalermo\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Palermo&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260601_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260601_OlivaPalermo"},"Ssd":"20260601","Name":"OlivaPalermo","Market":"ROW","Hash":"4355319130","FullDateString":"1. jun. 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Few places show their power quite like Everglades National Park in Florida, United States. From above, Florida's iconic wetlands unfold as a vast patchwork of shallow water, sawgrass, mangroves and winding channels, shaped by freshwater flowing slowly south from Lake Okeechobee.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.EvergladesWetlands_ROW3871146559_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.EvergladesWetlands_ROW3871146559_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Aerial view of Everglades National Park, Florida, United States","Copyright":"© Tetra Images/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260531_EvergladesWetlands\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Everglades+National+Park&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260531_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260531_EvergladesWetlands"},"Ssd":"20260531","Name":"EvergladesWetlands","Market":"ROW","Hash":"3871146559","FullDateString":"31. maj 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Etosha National Park, Namibia, is not a place for soft starts, and the plains zebra foal in this image seems to get the memo. In a land this vast—nearly 22,300 square kilometres of salt pans and grassland—timing is everything, and hesitation is expensive. Lions, spotted hyenas, wild dogs, cheetahs and leopards constantly pressure the herd—especially the youngest—so zebras are born ready. Minutes after arrival, they're upright. Hours later, they're moving.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.EquusQuagga_ROW3735095884_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.EquusQuagga_ROW3735095884_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Plains zebra foal in Etosha National Park, Namibia","Copyright":"© Sharon Heald/Nature Picture Library","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260530_EquusQuagga\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Plains+zebras&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260530_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260530_EquusQuagga"},"Ssd":"20260530","Name":"EquusQuagga","Market":"ROW","Hash":"3735095884","FullDateString":"30. maj 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"In Sagarmatha National Park, Nepal, Mount Everest rises into view, calm and unmoved as evening settles in. That stillness was broken in 1953. After years of planning and weeks of climbing, New Zealander Edmund Hillary and Sherpa mountaineer Tenzing Norgay reached the summit. At just under 8,850 metres above sea level, they became the first people known to have stood at Earth's highest point.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.SummitEverest_ROW0124036396_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.SummitEverest_ROW0124036396_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Mount Everest summit, Sagarmatha National Park, Nepal","Copyright":"© fotoVoyager/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260529_SummitEverest\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Mount+Everest&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260529_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260529_SummitEverest"},"Ssd":"20260529","Name":"SummitEverest","Market":"ROW","Hash":"0124036396","FullDateString":"29. maj 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"As night settles over Suwon, South Korea, the old city wall pictured here shows that function doesn't necessarily cancel out beauty—it can create it. Built between 1794 and 1796 under King Jeongjo of the Joseon Dynasty, Hwaseong Fortress was more than a barrier. It was policy in stone: a reform-minded push for a leaner, better-run state, driven by practicality and a deeply personal motive. Jeongjo ordered its construction to honour his father while strengthening a kingdom that wanted smarter systems, not just thicker walls.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.HwaesongFortress_ROW5120424335_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.HwaesongFortress_ROW5120424335_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Old city wall of Hwaseong Fortress, Suwon, South Korea","Copyright":"© aomam/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260528_HwaesongFortress\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Hwaseong+Fortress+Suwon&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260528_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260528_HwaesongFortress"},"Ssd":"20260528","Name":"HwaesongFortress","Market":"ROW","Hash":"5120424335","FullDateString":"28. maj 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Just look at this cutie swimming in the waters of Kachemak Bay in Alaska! Otters are captivating creatures that play an essential role in maintaining healthy ecosystems. Known for their playful behaviour and remarkable intelligence, otters are key indicators of waterway health. Sadly, they face growing challenges from habitat loss and pollution.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.OtterDay_ROW8950256578_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.OtterDay_ROW8950256578_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Sea otter, Kachemak Bay, Homer, Alaska, United States","Copyright":"© roclwyr/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260527_OtterDay\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Sea+Otter&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260527_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260527_OtterDay"},"Ssd":"20260527","Name":"OtterDay","Market